==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*mōdēr'', from Indo-European ''*māter-''.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Frisian [[modor|mōdor]], Old Saxon [[modor|mōdor]] (Dutch [[moeder]]), Old High German [[muotar]] (German [[Mutter]]), Old Franconian [[muoder]], Old Norse [[móðir]] (Swedish [[moder]]).

''Indo-European cognates:'' Vedic Sanskrit [[मातृ]], Avestan ''mātar-'', Doric Greek [[μάτηρ]], Latin [[mater|māter]], Slavic ''*mātī'' (Old Church Slavonic [[мати]], Russian [[мать]]), Baltic ''*mātē'' (Lithuanian [[mote|mōtē]], Latvian [[mate|mãte]]), Armenian [[մայր]], Celtic ''*māter-'' (Old Irish [[máthir]]), Tocharian A ''mācar''.

